<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP MUSIC REVIEW; SONGS OF ROMANTIC LONGING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICHARD CROMELIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 You might expect an American art-cabaret singer who based her career in 
Belgium for a decade to come equipped with a heavy Euro-attitude, but in her 
Los Angeles debut at LunaPark on Tuesday, Anna Domino didn't do any 
persona-pushing. The gaunt singer-songwriter projected a nervous, bemused 
manner, interspersing deadpan wisecracks between the songs. 
</P>
<P>
 Backed by her own accordion and meticulously supported by guitarist-banjoist 
Michel Delory and amazing percussionist Hearn Gadbois, she sang in a 
deceptively plain voice. With a suggestion of huskiness, it insinuates rather 
than asserts -- ideal for her twilight moods of romantic longing. 
</P>
<P>
 She expresses a touching vulnerability, but while her music is evocative and 
seductive, it isn't equipped to summon something like real despair. Her 
chilling version of the creepy song sung by the little girl in "Night of the 
Hunter" indicated she'd do well to move from pastels into the dark. RICHARD 
CROMELIN 
</P>
</TEXT>
