<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFF THE TICKER: MAYBE HE COULDN'T HANG THE DRAPES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Evelyn Y. Davis, a self-proclaimed stockholder activist known for bluntly 
advising corporate bosses to -- among other things -- get lost, said she has 
politely told her third husband to do the same. 
</P>
<P>
 Davis, 64, didn't explain the reasons for the divorce with Walter Froh, 66, a 
retired economist she married in August, 1991. 
</P>
<P>
 Davis, a millionaire with stock in 120 corporations, has been the buzz at the 
companies' past annual meetings. 
</P>
<P>
 She once gave May Department Stores Co. Chairman David C. Farrell a $1,600 
check and the warning: "David, please make sure your man is on time when he 
comes to hang my drapes. I'm a busy woman." 
</P>
