<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hick; Rick VanderKnyff, ; Eric Bailey 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 GOLDEN SEATS: For her upcoming singing appearances at Anaheim Arena, Barbra 
Streisand is letting several charity groups each buy 250 "Golden Circle" 
tickets to resell for their own fund raising. One of them is the Alliance for 
Children's Rights, based in Los Angeles. Its spokesman, Jeffrey Schwartz, calls 
it "a fantastic opportunity." . . . Adds Schwartz: "We still have to pay $350 
for each ticket, but we're selling them for $1,000 each, so we'll make a very 
nice profit." Scalper prices for Golden Circle tickets, he predicts, will go 
well above $1,000. 
</P>
<P>
 DEAN OF BOOKS: Books of all kinds can become collector's items, but fantasy 
and horror are areas of particular interest. (OC Live!) One of the most 
collectible authors in those genres is Dean Koontz of Newport Beach. First 
editions of some of his books, such as "Phantoms" and "Whispers," can sell for 
$300 and up. . . . "He's by far the biggest author in Orange County" among 
collectors, says James Cahill, of Cahill's Book Store in Fountain Valley. 
Nationally, "he's not quite as big as Stephen King, but he's close." 
</P>
<P>
 HIS INSPIRATION: Roxie Campanella did not get the publicity of her late 
husband, Roy, the Hall of Fame catcher for the Los Angeles Dodgers. But family 
friends credit her for being the inspiration for her husband, always at his 
side after his career was cut short when a car accident left him paralyzed. . . 
. Now she's in the spotlight herself. She'll be the speaker at the Anaheim 
Family YMCA's Good Friday services at the Anaheim Convention Center. 
</P>
<P>
 BREN BUCKS: Irvine Co. Chairman Donald Bren, a reclusive sort rarely seen or 
heard in public, lets his money do the talking when it comes to politics. Bren 
recently ponied up $50,000 to the campaign of Gov. Pete Wilson, a longtime 
chum. The cash accompanies another $50,000 the Irvine Co. has donated to the 
governor. . . . Such generosity isn't new for Bren. The developer has been 
helping Wilson since 1975, and hosted a fund-raiser for him in 1989 that 
brought in $86,200. 
</P>
