<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: SAN JUAN CAPISTRANO; CITY STAFF BACKS BID BY O'NEILL, 
PARTNER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEN HALL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A city staff report issued this week recommends that the City Council sell a 
key downtown commercial complex to South County rancher Richard J. O'Neill and 
his partner, Stephen A. Nordeck, for $1.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
 The report, which will be discussed during a public hearing at City Hall on 
Tuesday, indicates that O'Neill and Nordeck have agreed to make $686,550 in 
improvements to the block-long complex. It is located at the intersection of 
Camino Capistrano and Ortega Highway, directly across the street from historic 
Mission San Juan Capistrano. 
</P>
<P>
 A proposed agreement between the city and the developers, called San Juan 
Partners, will be reviewed by the council April 19. Based on earlier votes, the 
council is expected to approve the sale Tuesday and the development agreement 
two weeks later. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think we need to look out for what's best for the city, taking into 
consideration other local projects," Councilman Jeff Vasquez said Wednesday. 
"The O'Neill family has invested quite a bit into the city, particularly at the 
El Adobe restaurant. They have made a lot of upgrades to it, but still 
preserved its ambience . . . which is the kind of gradual development we want 
to see." 
</P>
<P>
 Acting as the Community Redevelopment Agency, which owns the complex, the 
council on Jan. 18 directed the city staff to enter into exclusive negotiations 
with O'Neill and Nordeck. Nordeck, a former mayor of Manhattan Beach and former 
county planning commissioner, is part owner of the well-known Swallows Inn, 
half a block away from the complex. 
</P>
<P>
 The vote for O'Neill and Nordeck was close, however, at 3 to 2, with Mayor 
Collene Campbell and Councilwoman Carolyn Nash opting for the second-place 
bidders, Riverside Community Investors. The RCI group has continued to lobby 
intensely for the bid, Vasquez said. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't think we have ever been lobbied as strongly about anything," Vasquez 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 The complex houses the Cafe Capistrano and the El Peon, among other small 
businesses.LEN HALL 
</P>
</TEXT>
