<HEADLINE>
<P>
SCHOOLS' MOCK-QUAKE DRILL UPSETS PRINCIPALS, PARENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BETH SHUSTER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Principals, teachers and parents are balking at a Los Angeles Unified School 
District plan to stage a mock 7.5 earthquake next week, claiming the drill 
would be an all-too-vivid reminder of January's magnitude 6.8 temblor. 
</P>
<P>
 Students still are too traumatized by the quake and its aftershocks and will 
not react well to an extensive practice drill, according to some critics. 
</P>
<P>
 The annual drill, scheduled for Tuesday, also could be difficult for teachers 
and other school staff members, who lost homes and possessions in the quake. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think we've had enough practice," said Maureen Diekmann, the principal at 
Van Gogh Street Elementary in Granada Hills, which remains closed -- with its 
students relocated -- because of earthquake damage. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're definitely not going to do the whole nine yards. We're not going to 
have anyone hurt and we're not going to have anyone stuck anywhere." 
</P>
<P>
 School district officials say that the drill, called Shake '94, is scheduled 
every year at this time to coincide with the state-designated Earthquake 
Preparedness Month and that it is particularly important this year to test 
schools' emergency plans. 
</P>
<P>
 "Do we stop everything?" said Jim Sugahara, a district administrator who 
oversees the emergency services office. "If you have a car accident, when do 
you go back in the car? How long do you want us to wait? I'd rather see our 
schools prepared and going through this exercise than not." 
</P>
<P>
 The bulletin sent to schools describing Shake '94 tells principals to simulate 
a magnitude 7.5 quake at 10:30 Tuesday morning. 
</P>
<P>
 "The impact upon the metropolitan Los Angeles area is significant," the memo 
says. "Power, water, gas, sewer and telephone systems fail in all areas. 
Freeway bridges have collapsed, critically disrupting the transportation 
system. Fires are reported at District sites. Hazardous materials are released 
into the air in South Gate. Superintendent Sidney A. Thompson declares a state 
of emergency and orders staff to remain at their sites." 
</P>
<P>
 The drill typically is elaborate. Students pretend to be injured or missing 
and some are carried off in stretchers. Teachers administer first-aid and 
conduct search-and-rescue missions. Others hold up signs depicting fires. A 
large aftershock hits 25 minutes into the drill. 
</P>
<P>
 This year, however, principals across the district say it will be a low-key 
affair. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't think the kids need to go through this -- they've been through enough 
already," said Dan Balderrama, the principal at Langdon Avenue School in North 
Hills, where about 70 students just returned after the January quake. "We'll 
just walk through it with the office staff and support people." 
</P>
<P>
 And at Canoga Park Elementary, Assistant Principal Sara Applebaum said: "We're 
still living it. We haven't stopped living it. Ideally, we'd like to not have 
to think about this again." 
</P>
<P>
 At Hobart Boulevard Elementary near Downtown, teachers will be told to keep 
reminding students that it is just a practice. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're trying to take every precaution so that our children won't be scared by 
it," said Betty Daniels, the assistant principal in charge of the drill. "My 
main emphasis will be to reassure the children that everything will be all 
right." 
</P>
<P>
 Rather than a 45-minute drill, most principals said they will scale it back to 
about 10 minutes and avoid giving students much description about the effects 
of the simulation. Some principals say students have just returned to school, 
others are sharing homes with two and three families, and still others are 
getting counseling because of quake trauma. 
</P>
<P>
 "The kids need more structure, more stability," said Debbie Moorman, whose 
daughter attends Kennedy High School in Granada Hills, where classroom 
buildings are closed and students take classes in portable bungalows. "I don't 
think it's wise right now. I think they should wait until at least the fall 
semester." 
</P>
<P>
 Schools are required to test their emergency communications plans and submit 
an evaluation of Shake '94. The questionnaire asks principals for 
recommendations to improve the schools' plans and whether any major problems 
developed during the exercise. 
</P>
<P>
 All district schools are required to have an emergency plan that includes 
having teachers assigned to various search-and-rescue and first-aid positions. 
Schools are required to have emergency supplies, but the level of preparedness 
is spotty throughout the district. 
</P>
<P>
 Some schools have enough supplies to keep students on campus for 72 hours 
after an emergency, while others barely have enough for the day. The district 
is reviewing its emergency plans and schools' supplies in the wake of the Jan. 
17 quake. 
</P>
<P>
 Emylou Ballard, the president of the 10th District Parent Teacher Student 
Assn., said local schools should decide how to conduct the drill and whether 
their students and staff can handle it. 
</P>
<P>
 "Maybe they should have more psychological mending and education (about 
quakes)," Ballard said. "But the more kids understand what will happen, the 
better they'll be able to handle a big earthquake." 
</P>
<P>
 Some parents and teachers agreed. Said Pamela Goldstein, a teacher at Van Nuys 
Elementary: "They (the students) really do need an avenue to talk. It's good to 
open it up for discussion." 
</P>
<P>
 But even with the drill, some parents and others say the schools still are 
unprepared for a quake. Practice, they say, won't make schools perfect. 
</P>
<P>
 "Schools just aren't ready and able to handle a big earthquake," said Helen 
Fallon, a parent who has criticized the district's quake readiness. "I think 
kids need to know that schools are prepared and safe." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA033194-0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 027947 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
