<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: SIMI VALLEY; 3 FIRMS TO BID ON POLICE STATION DESIGN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SARA CATANIA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Three architectural firms have been selected to bid on the design for a new 
multimillion-dollar police headquarters in Simi Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 The city's Civic Center Committee chose the top candidates from 10 
architectural firms applying for the right to assess the needs of the 
department and plan a new station. 
</P>
<P>
 Two of the three finalists have worked on other projects in Ventura County. 
</P>
<P>
 Leach Mounce Architects, the only firm among the finalists based in Ventura 
County, designed the Ventura County East Valley Sheriff's Station in Thousand 
Oaks and fire stations in Oxnard and Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
 Combs & Miguel, whose offices are in Sylmar and Valencia, designed the 
recently approved plans for Simi Valley's Cultural Arts Center. 
</P>
<P>
 The third finalist, San Jose-based Ruth & Going, teamed up with a public 
safety specialist to design and engineer the police headquarters in 
South-Central Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 The winning architect will oversee the first nine-month phase of the four-year 
project. The station could cost as much as $11.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
 "All three have done some very impressive work with police design," Mayor Greg 
Stratton said. "Since this is the first phase, rather than looking for someone 
who builds pretty buildings, we need someone who understands police 
departments." 
</P>
<P>
 In coming weeks, the finalists will be interviewed by the committee, made up 
of Stratton and Councilwoman Judy Mikels, along with City Manager Lin Koester, 
Police Chief Willard R. Schlieter and Deputy City Manager Bob Heitzman. 
</P>
<P>
 A final recommendation is scheduled to be made April 11 to the full City 
Council. SARA CATANIA 
</P>
</TEXT>
